Throughout landlocked Bolivia, the memory of the lost coast and now in Chile’s hands after a bloody conflict over resources in the 19th century is still alive, as is the desire to sail the Pacific Ocean once again.
These hopes have perhaps reached the highest level in decades, while Bolivia awaits the decision of the International Court of Justice on 1 October after five years of deliberations.
"Bolivia has momentum, a spirit of unity and serenity and obviously is waiting for the result with a positive attitude," said Roberto Calzadilla, a Bolivian diplomat.
Many Bolivians will look at the International Court of Justice ruling on big screens across the country, in the hope that the Hague tribunal will welcome Bolivia's claim that - after decades of intermittent dialogue - Chile is obliged to negotiate, granting Bolivia an outlet to the sea within the competence of the state.
