John Edward: Language skills are essential for global citizens
Scottish independent schools maintain a curriculum of academic excellence and this continued in 2018 with another set of outstanding exam results, reinforced by individual and collective success in sport, art, music and other collective endeavours.
With over 30,000 pupils across Scotland, these schools, represented by The Scottish Council of Independent Schools (SCIS), aim to provide the best level of service to their students and parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare students for further higher education, career choice and their place in the world as global citizens.
As an education sector able to develop and adopt a personalized school curriculum, we observe that modern languages continue to be a popular and in-demand subject within schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you speak to a man in a language he understands, the message will reach his brain.
If you speak to him in his native language, the message will reach the heart."
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely on English alone if we wish to build trusting relationships with people from other countries.
From the results of this year’s exams, we can see that languages are at the top of the rankings, with the highest success rates within independent schools.
68% of the pupils who studied foreign languages obtained the highest marks.
The data, collected from the 74 SCIS member schools, showed that 72% of students obtained the highest praise grade in Chinese, while 72% of those who studied German, 69% of those who studied French and 63% of those who studied Spanish obtained the maximum grade.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland are promoting foreign languages as core skills for children and young people, who will undoubtedly need them in the future.
Currently, languages, as a choice of subject, are considered at the same level as STEM subjects (science, technology, technique and mathematics) in the curricula of independent institutions and elsewhere.
A survey conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission in 2014 found that the reasons employees indicated for difficulty in covering jobs were attributable in 17% of cases to a lack of language skills.
For this reason, language skills are becoming increasingly essential to prepare young people for their future careers.
With more and more job opportunities requiring language skills, these skills are essential in a globalised world.
Regardless of your chosen career, if you have learned a second language, you will have an effective advantage in the future with a life-long competence like this.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries will bring a multilingual person automatically ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of over 4,000 adults in the UK in 2013, 75% were unable to speak a foreign language to a level sufficient to sustain a conversation and French was the only language spoken by a two-digit percentage, 15%.
That is why investing in language teaching is so important for children today.
Knowledge of several languages, in particular those of developing economies, will give children a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will differ in the languages taught.
Several schools will focus on the more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered the most important for the UK looking to 2020, such as Mandarin Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests, there will always be several languages to choose from in independent schools, with teaching staff specialised in this area.
Scottish independent schools are dedicated to providing a learning environment that will prepare children and equip them with the skills necessary for success, whatever their future may be.
It is not possible to deny at this time, in a global trading system, that languages continue to be fundamental to the future of the country, and this must be reflected in teaching.
In fact, modern languages should be considered “international communication skills.”
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Independent Schools.
