North Korea Refuses to Unilateral Disarmament Without Trust
North Korea’s foreign minister told the United Nations on Saturday that maintaining sanctions was exacerbating the country’s mistrust of the United States, which in such circumstances would absolutely refuse to unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons.
Ri Yong Ho told the UN General Assembly that North Korea had taken "important goodwill measures" over the past year, such as stopping nuclear and missile tests, dismantling the nuclear test site and committing to non-proliferation of nuclear weapons and nuclear technology.
“However, we do not see any compliant response from the US,” he said.
“Without trust in the United States, there will be no security in our national security, and in such circumstances we absolutely refuse to unilaterally disarm first.”
Although Ri repurposed the complaints about Washington’s resistance to a “phased” denuclearization with which North Korea would be rewarded based on gradual actions, his statement was important because he did not reject unilateral denuclearization in its entirety as Pyongyang has done in the past.
Ri referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump during the first-ever meeting between a sitting US president and a North Korean leader, held in Singapore on June 12, when Kim pledged to work toward the “denuclearization of the Korean Peninsula,” while Trump promised guarantees to North Korean security.
North Korea has sought a formal end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said Pyongyang must give up its nuclear weapons first.
Washington has also opposed calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
“The US insists on the need to ‘have denuclearisation first’ and to increase the level of pressure with sanctions to achieve their purpose in a coercive way and even opposes the ‘declaration of an end to the war,’” Ri said.
“The idea that sanctions can bring us to our knees is an illusion of those who know nothing about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is increasing our mistrust.”
Ri made no reference to plans for a second meeting between Kim and Trump that the U.S. leader had announced at the U.N. earlier this week.
The minister instead pointed out the three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in over the past 5 months and added: "If the counterpart of this denuclearization issue were South Korea and not the US, the denuclearization of the Korean peninsula would not be at this point dead."
But even so, the tone of Ri’s speech was markedly different from last year’s speech at the UN General Assembly, when he said it was inevitable to target US territory with North Korean missiles after “evil president” Trump called Kim a “missile man” engaged in a suicide mission.
Ahead of the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "completely destroy" North Korea, heaped praise on Kim for his courage in embarking on the path of disarmament, but said much more had to be done and sanctions would remain in place until North Korea was denuclearized.
On Wednesday, Trump said he doesn’t have a deadline, saying “if it takes two years, three years or five months, it doesn’t matter.”
China and Russia say the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for its actions.
However, U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "compliance with Security Council sanctions must continue vigorously and without exception until complete, final and proven denuclearization is achieved."
The Security Council unanimously backed sanctions on North Korea in 2006 in an attempt to stifle funding for nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and later said he would visit Pyongyang again the following month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea already three times this year, but the last trip did not go well.
He departed Pyongyang in July saying progress had been made, but a few hours later North Korea accused him of making “gangster demands.”
North Korea had pledged during a meeting this month with Moon to dismantle a missile site and a nuclear complex if the U.S. took "conforming measures."
He said Kim had explained to him that the “conforming measures” he wanted were security guarantees Trump had committed to in Singapore and actions toward a normalization of relations with Washington.
Harvard students take a course on how to get enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year has pushed all its students to sleep more in an attempt to counter the growing manly culture of studying for whole nights fed on caffeine.
One university scholar found that students at the world’s number one university often have no idea of the basic concepts of self-care.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women’s Hospital, developed the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the U.S.
He had the idea to start the course after a lecture he had given on the impact of lack of sleep on learning.
“Finally a girl came to me and said, ‘Why am I only being told this now, when I’m senior year?’
She said no one had ever told her anything about the importance of sleep, which surprised me a lot," she told The Telegraph.
The course, taught for the first time this year, explains to students the essential concepts of how good sleep-related habits can help academic and athletic performance, as well as improve overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university’s director general of health services, said the university decided to introduce the course after discovering that students suffered from a severe lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive activities.
In one section there is an image of a dormitory room, where students can select coffee cups, curtains, sneakers and books to learn about the effects of caffeine and light and how athletic performance is affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of an evening routine.
In another section, participants are explained how lack of long-term sleep can increase the risks of heart attacks, strokes, depression, and cancer.
A campus map, with interactive icons, then encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that it will not immediately change the behavior of students.
But we believe that they have a right to know, just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke cigarettes," added Prof. Czeisler.
The culture of pride tied to the “night out studying” still exists, he said, adding that modern technology and increasing pressure on students lead to lack of sleep being an ever-growing problem.
Getting enough sleep and having good quality sleep should be the students’ “secret weapon” to combat stress, fatigue, anxiety, explained and even should serve to avoid gaining weight as lack of sleep brings the brain into starvation mode, making people constantly hungry.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian student enrolled in the faculty of chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Czeisler develop the course, after taking one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He explained that the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to promote a campus-wide course.
The next step, he hopes, will be to ask all graduate students to follow a similar program of study before enrolling at this competitive institution.
Prof. Czeisler advised students to set an alarm for when they have to go to bed, as well as for when they have to wake up, and to be aware of the harmful effects of the "blue light" emitted by electronic screens and LED lights, which can tilt the circadian rhythm, leading to sleeping problems.
