New cancer vaccine may teach immune system to ‘see’ malignant cells and kill them
Vaccine Teaches Immune System to Recognize Malignant Cells as Part of Treatment
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient, and altering them in the laboratory.
They can then "see" a protein common to many types of cancer and are then re-injected.
An experimental trial of this vaccine is giving promising results in patients with different types of cancer.
A woman treated with the vaccine that teaches the immune system to recognize malignant cells has seen her ovarian cancer disappear for over 18 months.
The method involves extracting immune cells from a patient and altering them in the laboratory so that they can “see” a protein common to numerous types of cancer, called HER2, and then those cells are injected again.
Professor Jay Berzofsky, from the US National Cancer Institute based in Bethesda, Maryland, said: "Our results indicate that we have a very promising vaccine."
The HER2 protein "promotes the growth of several types of cancer," including breast, ovarian, lung and colorectal cancers, Berzofsky said.
