The National Trust for Scotland scientists’ study will follow common and soprano bats, as well as brown eared and Daubenton bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recorders will be placed in key locations around the property to track the activities of the bats during the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct mobile investigations using portable detectors.
Analysis of recorded sounds by an expert will determine the frequency of bat calls and how each species behaves.
A habitat map and report will then be produced to create a detailed, scaled-up picture of their behaviour.
Rob Dewar, a nature conservation consultant for the NTS, hopes the results will reveal which areas of habitat are most important to bats and how these are used by each species.
This information will help determine the benefits of habitat management work, such as creating lawns, and how to best maintain forests for bats and other related species.
The population of bats in Scotland and the United Kingdom has declined considerably in the last century.
Bats are at risk due to construction and development work affecting perches and ruining habitat.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a threat, as can flypaper and some chemical treatments of building materials, in addition to domestic cat attacks.
Bats aren't really blind.
However, due to their nocturnal hunting habits, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to grabbing prey.
They use a sophisticated eco-localization technique to locate insects and obstacles on their trajectory.
The NTS, responsible for the care of over 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
Ten qualified experts regularly conduct investigations, inspect the perches and sometimes carry out rescues.
The organisation has even set up Scotland’s first bat-only reserve at the Threate estate in the Dumfries and Galloway region, which is home to eight of Scotland’s ten bat species.
Estate manager David Thompson says the property is the ideal territory.
“Here at Threate we have a large area for bats,” he said.
“We have ancient buildings, many centuries-old trees and a good habitat.
But there’s a lot about bats that we don’t know yet, so the work we do here and at other properties will help us understand more about their growth needs.”
It stresses the importance of checking bats before conducting maintenance within properties as it is possible that unintentional destruction of a single maternal perch could kill up to 400 females and young, perhaps wiping out an entire local population.
Bats are protected and it is illegal to kill them, harass them, disturb them or destroy their perches.
Elisabeth Ferrell, Scottish head of the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the public to help.
He said: “We still have a lot to learn about our bats and for many of our species we don’t know how their populations fare.”
