Red Tide Update: Concentration Declines in Pinellas, Manatee, and Sarasota
The Florida Fish and Wildlife Commission’s latest report shows an overall decrease in red tide concentration in parts of the Tampa Bay area.
According to the FWC, patchy flowering conditions, which suggest a decrease in concentration, are evident in the areas of Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties.
The red tide bloom stretches for about 130 miles of coastline from northern Pinellas County to southern Lee County.
The patches are about 10 miles off Hillsborough County but in fewer areas than last week.
The red tide was also observed in Pasco County.
Last week an average concentration was reported in Pinellas County or off its coast, a low to high concentration off Hillsborough County, a background concentration to a high concentration in Manatee County, a background concentration to a high concentration in Sarasota County or off its coast, a background concentration to a high concentration in Lee County, or a background concentration to a concentration off its coast.
Cases of respiratory irritation continue to be reported in Pinellas, Manatee, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reported cases in northwestern Florida in the past week.
